    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "dd886f962792a07f",
      "text": "# Legal Status & Location"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "bf2bea200c0c1a89",
      "text": "Subak is a social commons among farmers in Bali [[Australia/Oceania]] [[bioregional]]; it is not a formal organization and thus has no formal legal status. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "34785ce921da77a6",
      "text": "# When did it start? "
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "f55c16f46da9f224",
      "text": "Subak practices to help manage rice planting and irrigation have been around for generations in Bali, but they were marginalized in the 1960s when the Green Revolution introduced \"miracle\" rice varieties, pesticides and fertilizers. In the face of \"modern\" ways of growing rice, farmers clung to their traditional religious rituals at water temples as part of their cultivation practices. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "46b61bcfb6925803",
      "text": "# How do they work?"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "0e69251b47b72394",
      "text": "Anthropologist J. Stephen Lansing [https://www.santafe.edu/people/profile/j-stephen-lansing html] figured out that the rituals were not simply religious conservatism, but a social/cultural way of coordinating farmers to plant rice at different times in the season (to avoid water shortages) but to harvest rice at the same time (to minimize pests proliferating). As Lansing explains in his book Perfect Order [http://press.princeton.edu/titles/8186.html html], subak irrigation re-emerged in the 1980s as the failures of western industrial agriculture became apparent. It works by using social and religious practices to sync with the best ecological timing for planting and harvesting."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "bcb1cb0f6546a4b1",
      "text": "# How are they financed?"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "d18d3472ad6ba440",
      "text": "As a system driven by social practice and tradition, subak has no direct financial or monetary costs.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
