        "text": "Subak has been around for generations in Bali, but it was marginalized in the 1960s when the Green Revolution introduced farming fueled by \"miracle\" rice varieties, pesticides and fertilizers. In the face of \"modern\" ways of growing rice, farmers clung to their traditional religious rituals at water temples as part of their cultivation practices. Anthropologist Steve Lansing [https://www.santafe.edu/people/profile/j-stephen-lansing html] figured out that the rituals were not simply religious conservatism, but a social/cultural way of coordinating farmers to plant rice at different times in the season (to avoid water shortages) but to harvest rice at the same time (to minimize pests proliferating). Subak irrigation re-emerged in the 1980s and after."
