        "id": "250887ea9ab807d5",
        "text": "- [[Cultivate Shared Purpose & Values]]\n- [[Ensure Fair Abundance]] \n- [[Strengthen the Nested-I]]\n- [[Decouple Giving & Taking]] \n- [[Practice Gentle Reciprocity]]  \n- [[Honor Care]]\n- [[Deepen Interdependency on Nature]]\n\nAnthroplogist Steven Lansing writes: Farmers easily fell into a routine of purchasing \"technology packets\" and selling their crops for cash, which could be used to purchase consumer goods such as motorcyles. But it turned out that there were hidden environmental costs. Rice pests soon acquired resistance to pesticides. The agricultural service responded by prescribing more pesticides. Within a few years resistant pests such as the brown leafhopper were devastating rice crops, in some areas consuming the entire harvest. While the extension service turned to aerial pesticide-spraying campaigns, the farmers found a more effective solution by returning to the old system of coordinated region-wide fallow periods, organized by water temples. Pesticide usage declined, but meanwhile it was becoming apparent that the technology packets were triggering another major environmental crisis. The fertilizer contained in these packets included phosphate and potassium, minerals that are naturally abundant in the volcanic soil of Bali.\n\n   \n- [[Trust Situated Knowing]] & Be Creatively Adaptive\n- [[Preserve Relationships in Addressing Conflicts]]\n- [[Reflect on Your Peer-Governance]]"
